&gt; &gt;It might be better for the @Parameters method to return an
&gt; &gt;Iterator, allowing the lazy creation of substantial data structures,
&gt; &gt;however.
&gt; &gt;  @Parameters static Iterator&lt;Object[]&gt; data() ...
&gt; &gt;  
&gt; &gt;
&gt;   Iterator won&#39;t allow to jump directly to the specific test. 
&gt; It would 
&gt; be useful for IDE runners if user would like to restart only specific 
&gt; test case (this scenario us currently not supported in 
&gt; Eclipse&#39;s JUnit 
&gt; runner).

Agreed. AbstractCollection or AbstractList might be better.

&gt; 
&gt; &gt;&gt;  Second limitation is that user don&#39;t have will have to 
&gt; &gt;&gt;declaratively 
&gt; &gt;&gt;specify test data sets without writing custom @Parameters 
&gt; &gt;&gt;method and use 
&gt; &gt;&gt;some system property to differentiate between tests. Perhaps 
&gt; &gt;&gt;you can add 
&gt; &gt;&gt;some &quot;name&quot; property to Parameters annotation, so test runner 
&gt; &gt;&gt;can match 
&gt; &gt;&gt;this name with declared test data. Such name property would 
&gt; &gt;&gt;also allow 
&gt; &gt;&gt;to have multiple @Parameters methods and match them with 
&gt; &gt;&gt;@Test methods 
&gt; &gt;&gt;if you&#39;ll have same name there too. The last would allow to 
&gt; &gt;&gt;have several 
&gt; &gt;&gt;test methods with different kinds of test parameters 
&gt; without creating 
&gt; &gt;&gt;separate test classes (so you&#39;ll have single test class for 
&gt; &gt;&gt;class under 
&gt; &gt;&gt;testing).
&gt; &gt;&gt;    
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;I don&#39;t understand this objection. Can you write an example 
&gt; of what you
&gt; &gt;would like to see?
&gt; &gt;  
&gt; &gt;
&gt;   Ok. I may have several data sets (e.g. small one for smoke 
&gt; testing and 
&gt; a really huge one for complete regression testing) and I want 
&gt; to choose 
&gt; between them from the runner. For instance:
&gt; 
&gt; @Parameters(name=&quot;smoke&quot;) public static Object[] data() {
&gt;   return new int[][] {{0, 0}, {1, 1}};
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; @Parameters(name=&quot;full&quot;) public static Object[] data() {
&gt;   // load data from external file or generate permutations
&gt;   return data;
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt;   Then you&#39;ll specify test type &quot;smoke&quot; or &quot;full&quot; on a runner and it 
&gt; will choose an appropriate set of the test data.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt;&gt;  The last thing I&#39;d like to mention is that current 
&gt; &gt;&gt;@Parameters methods 
&gt; &gt;&gt;won&#39;t scale to large data sets (the same limitation also exists in 
&gt; &gt;&gt;TestNG). I&#39;ve seen JUnit3 suite() methods that produced 
&gt; thousands of 
&gt; &gt;&gt;test permutations and that required lots of memory memory 
&gt; &gt;&gt;when running 
&gt; &gt;&gt;tests. So, It think that it would make sense to introduce an 
&gt; &gt;&gt;interface 
&gt; &gt;&gt;similar to JDBC ResultSet, so test runner can create iterate 
&gt; &gt;&gt;trough test 
&gt; &gt;&gt;data without loading it completely into memory and also have 
&gt; &gt;&gt;option to 
&gt; &gt;&gt;get number of tests as well as jump to Nth test. You can also 
&gt; &gt;&gt;provide an 
&gt; &gt;&gt;adapter that will take Object[][] and provide all that 
&gt; &gt;&gt;functionality for 
&gt; &gt;&gt;users who don&#39;t want to create test data dynamically.
&gt; &gt;&gt;    
&gt; &gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;Would the Iterator version satisfy the need to handle large 
&gt; data sets?
&gt; &gt;  
&gt; &gt;
&gt;   The limitation of the iterator is that it does not provide a random 
&gt; access. This would make difficult to rerun only selected test 
&gt; case (e.g. 
&gt; failed one)
&gt; 
&gt;   regards,
